<header>
  <h1>Derivatives</h1>
  <p>The speedometer of mathematics.</p>
</header>

<h2>1. What's a derivative?</h2>

<p>
  Think about driving a car. Your GPS tracks your position over time.
  But your <em>speedometer</em> shows something different &mdash; not where you are,
  but <strong>how fast your position is changing right now</strong>.
</p>

<p>
  That's a derivative. Given any curve, the derivative tells you its slope at any point &mdash;
  how steeply it's rising or falling at that exact moment.
</p>

<h2>2. How do you actually find it?</h2>

<p>
  Here's the trick. Pick a point on a curve. Draw a line through it and a nearby point &mdash;
  that's called a <strong>secant line</strong>, and its slope is just rise over run.
</p>

<p>
  Now slide that second point closer and closer to the first.
  The secant line tilts and settles into one final position: the <strong>tangent line</strong>.
  That's the line that just grazes the curve at your point, and its slope <em>is</em> the derivative.
</p>

<div class="limit-demo">
  <p style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 0.9rem; color: #8892a4; margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
    The orange line connects two points. As they get closer, it becomes the purple tangent line.
  </p>
  <button class="animate-btn" id="animBtn">&#9654; Animate</button>
  <canvas id="secantCanvas" width="640" height="260"></canvas>
</div>
<div
  class="viz-qa viz-qa-standalone"
  data-viz-id="secant-to-tangent"
  data-viz-title="Secant to Tangent Animation"
  data-viz-desc="The orange secant line between two points on the curve approaches the purple tangent line as h shrinks to zero."
></div>

<p>
  Mathematically, we write this "sliding closer" process as a limit. If we call the gap between
  the two points <em>h</em>, then as h shrinks to zero:
</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <span class="math-display" data-tex="f'(x) = \\lim_{h \\to 0} \\frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}"></span>
  <p style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 0.82rem; color: #8892a4; margin: 1rem 0 0.5rem;">Every symbol, explained:</p>
  <table class="sym-table">
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="f"></span></td>
      <td>the name of your function &mdash; just a label, like calling it "the curve"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="x"></span></td>
      <td>the input &mdash; a position on the horizontal axis</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="f(x)"></span></td>
      <td>read "f of x" &mdash; the output (height) of the function at position x</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="f'(x)"></span></td>
      <td>read "f prime of x" &mdash; the derivative, what we're solving for. The tick mark means "derivative of"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="="></span></td>
      <td>equals &mdash; the derivative is defined as everything on the right side</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\lim"></span></td>
      <td>short for "limit" &mdash; the value an expression settles toward as something changes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\to"></span></td>
      <td>read "approaches" &mdash; gets closer and closer to, without necessarily reaching it</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="h \\to 0"></span></td>
      <td>h approaches zero &mdash; the gap between the two points gets infinitely small</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="h"></span></td>
      <td>the horizontal gap between two nearby points on the curve</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="f(x+h)"></span></td>
      <td>the height of the curve at a point h units to the right of x</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="f(x+h) - f(x)"></span></td>
      <td>the vertical change between the two points (the rise)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\dfrac{\\text{top}}{\\text{bottom}}"></span></td>
      <td>a fraction bar &mdash; means <em>divided by</em>. Top &divide; bottom. So <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}"></span> means <span class="math-inline" data-tex="(f(x+h)-f(x)) \\div h"></span></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><span class="math-inline" data-tex="h"></span> (bottom)</td>
      <td>the horizontal distance between the two points (the run) &mdash; rise &divide; run = slope</td>
    </tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="callout orange">
  Don't let the notation scare you. It's just: <em>(change in y) / (change in x)</em>, with the gap made infinitely small.
</div>

<h2>3. See it for yourself</h2>

<p>
  Move the slider to place a point anywhere on the curve.
  The highlighted tangent line shows the derivative at that spot.
  <span style="color:#f97316">Orange</span> means positive slope and <span style="color:#60a5fa">blue</span> means negative.
  Try moving to a peak, a valley, or where the curve is steepest.
</p>

<div class="graph-section">
