<div
  class="viz-qa viz-qa-standalone"
  data-viz-id="tangent-explorer"
  data-viz-title="Interactive Tangent Explorer"
  data-viz-desc="You choose a function and x-value, and the graph shows the tangent line and derivative at that exact point."
></div>

<div class="callout">
  <strong>Flat curve?</strong> Slope is 0 &mdash; the function isn't changing.<br/>
  <strong>Going up?</strong> Positive derivative. <strong>Going down?</strong> Negative.<br/>
  <strong>At a peak or valley?</strong> The derivative is exactly 0 there.
</div>

<h2>4. Shortcuts (you rarely need the limit)</h2>

<p>
  The limit is the <em>definition</em>, but computing it every time would be tedious.
  Mathematicians worked out a handful of rules that cover almost everything you'll encounter:
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-name">Power Rule &mdash; x to a power</div>
    <span class="math-display" data-tex="\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1}"></span>
    <div class="sym-list">
      <span class="sym">d/dx</span> &mdash; "take the derivative of." Written as a fraction: a tiny change in output over a tiny change in x.<br/>
      <span class="sym">n</span> &mdash; any fixed number (the exponent)<br/>
      <span class="sym">nx<sup>n-1</sup></span> &mdash; multiply by n, drop the exponent by 1
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-name">Constants don't change</div>
    <span class="math-display" data-tex="\\frac{d}{dx} c = 0"></span>
    <div class="sym-list">
      <span class="sym">c</span> &mdash; any fixed number, like 5 or &pi;<br/>
      <span class="sym">0</span> &mdash; a constant never changes, so its rate of change is zero
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-name">Sum Rule &mdash; split it up</div>
    <span class="math-display" data-tex="(f + g)' = f' + g'"></span>
    <div class="sym-list">
      <span class="sym">f, g</span> &mdash; any two functions<br/>
      <span class="sym">'</span> &mdash; "prime" shorthand for "derivative of"<br/>
      just differentiate each piece separately
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-name">Product Rule &mdash; two things multiplied</div>
    <span class="math-display" data-tex="(fg)' = f'g + fg'"></span>
    <div class="sym-list">
      <span class="sym">fg</span> &mdash; two functions multiplied<br/>
      <span class="sym">f'g</span> &mdash; derivative of f, times g as-is<br/>
      <span class="sym">fg'</span> &mdash; f as-is, times derivative of g<br/>
      add those two together
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-name">Chain Rule &mdash; function inside a function</div>
    <span class="math-display" data-tex="\\frac{d}{dx} f(g(x)) = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)"></span>
    <div class="sym-list">
      <span class="sym">g(x)</span> &mdash; the inner function<br/>
      <span class="sym">f(g(x))</span> &mdash; outer function wrapping g<br/>
      <span class="sym">f'(g(x))</span> &mdash; derivative of the outer<br/>
      <span class="sym">g'(x)</span> &mdash; derivative of the inner<br/>
      multiply them together
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-name">e^x is its own derivative</div>
    <span class="math-display" data-tex="\\frac{d}{dx} e^x = e^x"></span>
    <div class="sym-list">
      <span class="sym">e</span> &mdash; Euler's number &asymp; 2.718, a special mathematical constant<br/>
      <span class="sym">e^x</span> &mdash; the result equals the original &mdash; completely unique!
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="callout green">
  <strong>Quick example:</strong> Take <span class="math-inline" data-tex="f(x) = x^3 - 2x^2 + 5"></span>.
  Apply the power rule to each term:<br/><br/>
  <span class="math-inline" data-tex="f'(x) = 3x^2 - 4x"></span><br/><br/>
  At <span class="math-inline" data-tex="x = 2"></span>, that's
  <span class="math-inline" data-tex="3(4) - 4(2) = 4"></span> &mdash;
  the curve is rising with slope 4 at that point.
</div>

<h2>5. Why does any of this matter?</h2>

<p>
  Derivatives show up everywhere something is changing:
</p>

<ul style="margin: 0 0 1rem 1.5rem; line-height: 2.2;">
  <li><strong>Physics:</strong> velocity is the derivative of position; acceleration is the derivative of velocity.</li>
  <li><strong>Machine learning:</strong> training a neural network means following derivatives downhill to minimize error.</li>
  <li><strong>Engineering:</strong> finding the peak efficiency of an engine means finding where the derivative is zero.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Whenever you need to find the <em>best</em> value of something, or understand how fast something is changing,
  you reach for a derivative.
</p>

<section class="guide">
  <p class="guide-intro">A different kind of explanation</p>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">1</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>Zoom in on anything smooth</h3>
      <p>
        Take a hill. From far away it's curved &mdash; rolling, organic, complicated.
        Now walk up close. The ground in front of your feet looks flat.
        Walk closer still &mdash; just staring at a tiny patch of dirt. Completely flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not an illusion. Any smooth curve, when you zoom in far enough, <em>becomes</em> a straight line.
        This is one of the most profound things in all of mathematics, and you can verify it yourself
        right now by zooming into the interactive graph above.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-pull">
        The derivative is what any smooth curve turns into when you zoom in close enough.
      </div>
      <p>
        And a straight line has exactly one thing worth knowing about it: its <strong>slope</strong>.
        How steeply it rises or falls. That slope &mdash; that single number &mdash; is the derivative at that point.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">2</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>Every point gets its own number</h3>
      <p>
        Move to a different spot on the curve. Zoom in there. You get a different line, a different slope,
        a different number.
      </p>
      <p>
        So the derivative isn't <em>a</em> number. It's a whole function &mdash; one number for every
        point on the original curve. You feed it an x, it tells you the slope there.
        That's why we write <span class="math-inline" data-tex="f'(x)"></span> and not just <span class="math-inline" data-tex="f'"></span>.
        The x is asking: <em>"the slope at this specific x, please."</em>
      </p>
      <p>
        Try it in the graph above. Drag the slider left and right. Watch the slope number change.
        That changing number is the derivative function, live.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">3</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>You have felt this your entire life</h3>
      <p>
        You know the difference between going 60 mph and <em>accelerating</em> to 60 mph.
        One is a position-over-time situation. The other is a <em>how fast is the speed itself changing</em> situation.
        That second one is a derivative.
      </p>
      <p>
        When a car floors it and you get pressed into your seat &mdash; that pressure is your body
        detecting the derivative of velocity. You are a derivative sensor. You have been your whole life.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-examples">
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Your position</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">the original function</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Your speed</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">the derivative of position</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Your acceleration</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">the derivative of speed (derivative of a derivative)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">That jolt feeling</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">the derivative of acceleration. Yes, it goes further.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        Physics runs on derivatives, all the way down. Every force, every motion, every field &mdash;
        all relationships between quantities and their rates of change.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">4</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>The sign tells you the direction</h3>
      <p>
        The derivative is a number. That number can be positive, negative, or zero.
        And those three cases tell you everything about which way the curve is heading.
      </p>
      <p>
        Think of it like this. You're standing on a hillside and you take one step forward.
        Are you going uphill, downhill, or on flat ground?
      </p>
      <div class="guide-examples">
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Derivative &gt; 0</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">the function is climbing &mdash; one step right means higher up</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Derivative &lt; 0</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">the function is falling &mdash; one step right means lower down</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Derivative = 0</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">perfectly flat right here &mdash; neither up nor down, not even a little</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        That's it. Positive means going up. Negative means going down. Zero means flat.
        The sign of the derivative <em>is</em> the direction of change. Every time, no exceptions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">5</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>The size tells you how committed it is</h3>
      <p>
        The sign tells you direction. The <em>size</em> of the number tells you intensity.
      </p>
      <p>
        A derivative of 0.01 means: yes, technically going up, but barely &mdash; almost flat,
        creeping forward. A derivative of 50 means: going up aggressively, nearly vertical.
        Both positive. Very different feelings.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-pull">
        A big derivative means fast change. A small derivative means slow change. Zero means no change at all.
      </div>
      <p>
        This is why the speedometer analogy is so good. The <em>direction</em> the needle points is the sign &mdash;
        forward or backward. The <em>number on the gauge</em> is the magnitude. Both together give you the full picture
        of what change is doing at this moment.
      </p>
      <p>
        Look at <span class="math-inline" data-tex="x^2"></span> in the graph above. Near zero, the slope is tiny
        &mdash; the curve is almost flat. Move further out and the slope grows. Same direction (upward),
        but increasingly committed to it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">6</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>Zero is where things get interesting</h3>
      <p>
        When the derivative is zero, the function has gone flat for a moment. And that moment is special,
        because flat is the only way to switch from going up to going down.
      </p>
      <p>
        Imagine a ball thrown into the air. It rises. Then it falls. But to go from rising to falling,
        it has to pass through a single instant where it's doing <em>neither</em>. That instant &mdash;
        the peak &mdash; is where the derivative of its height is exactly zero.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-pull">
        Every mountain peak, every valley floor, every turnaround point &mdash; the derivative is zero there.
      </div>
      <p>
        This is one of the most powerful things in all of applied mathematics: to find where
        something is maximum or minimum, find where its derivative equals zero. That's how engineers
        find peak efficiency, how economists find optimal prices, how your GPS finds the shortest route.
        All of them are hunting for zeros of derivatives.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">7</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>Direction of change has direction of change</h3>
      <p>
        Here's a thought that might bend your brain a little.
      </p>
      <p>
        The derivative tells you which direction something is changing. But that direction of change
        is itself changing. It can change slowly or quickly, start to reverse, speed up.
        So you can take the derivative of the derivative.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is called the <strong>second derivative</strong>, and it tells you not where something is,
        not how fast it's changing, but <em>how fast the rate of change is changing</em>.
        Whether the change is accelerating or slowing down.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-examples">
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Position</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">where you are</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Velocity</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">how fast position is changing (1st derivative)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Acceleration</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">how fast velocity is changing (2nd derivative)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Jerk</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">how fast acceleration is changing (3rd derivative) &mdash; yes, this is the real name</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        "Jerk" is what you feel when a car's acceleration suddenly changes &mdash; that lurch.
        Engineers who design smooth elevators and trains are literally minimizing jerk.
        Derivatives go as deep as you need them to.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">8</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>Following the slope downhill</h3>
      <p>
        Here's how you train almost every AI model that exists today.
      </p>
      <p>
        Imagine you're blindfolded on a hilly landscape, trying to find the lowest valley.
        You can't see anything, but you can feel the ground beneath your feet.
        Which way is it sloping? Step that way. Check again. Step that way again.
        Repeat until the ground feels flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's gradient descent &mdash; the algorithm behind neural networks. The "landscape" is a
        function describing how wrong the model is. The derivative tells you which direction is downhill
        (toward less wrong). Take a small step. Repeat millions of times.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-pull">
        The derivative doesn't just describe change. It tells you which way to move to make things better.
      </div>
      <p>
        Every time you use a language model, a recommendation system, an image classifier &mdash;
        it exists because someone followed derivatives downhill, millions of steps, until the error hit a valley.
        The derivative of a loss function is the compass. Direction of change, put to work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">9</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>The world is lousy with them</h3>
      <p>
        Once you know what a derivative is, you start seeing them everywhere.
        They hide behind words like <em>rate</em>, <em>speed</em>, <em>growth</em>, <em>decline</em>,
        <em>sensitivity</em>, <em>trend</em>.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-examples">
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Temperature falling</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">derivative of temperature with respect to time</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Stock rising steeply</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">large positive derivative of price</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Ball at its peak</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">derivative of height = 0 (momentarily not going up or down)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">Heart rate spiking</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">large derivative of beats-per-minute</span>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-example">
          <span class="ex-label">A neural net training</span>
          <span class="ex-meaning">following derivatives of error downhill, step by step</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        If something can change &mdash; and everything can &mdash; then its derivative exists and
        is worth knowing.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-step">
    <div class="guide-step-num">10</div>
    <div class="guide-step-body">
      <h3>It only cares about right now</h3>
      <p>
        Here's the strangest and most beautiful thing about a derivative.
      </p>
      <p>
        It doesn't care where the curve has been. It doesn't care where it's going.
        It only knows one instant &mdash; the one you're looking at &mdash; and it asks:
        <em>at this exact moment, which direction is this heading, and how fast?</em>
      </p>
      <p>
        A photograph captures a position. A video captures positions over time.
        The derivative captures something a camera can't: <strong>tendency</strong>. Momentum. The direction of now.
      </p>
      <div class="guide-pull">
        The derivative is mathematics in the present tense.
      </div>
      <p>
        Everything else in a function &mdash; its history, its future, its shape &mdash; is irrelevant.
        The derivative collapses all of that into a single, present-tense number: <em>the slope right here.</em>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-reveal">
    <p>So what is a derivative, really?</p>
    <p class="big">The slope of a curve at a single point &mdash;<br/>the number that captures the direction of change, right now.</p>
    <p style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: #9d8fcc;">
      Everything else &mdash; the limit, the formula, the rules &mdash; is just machinery for computing that number.
    </p>
  </div>

</section>

<section class="visuals">
  <h2>Interactive visualizations</h2>
  <p style="color: var(--muted); font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">
    Four different windows into the same idea.
  </p>

  <!-- Twin Curves -->
  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">Twin Curves</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">Pick any point x and a nearby point x+h. The dashed secant line connects them. Shrink h toward zero and watch it settle into the tangent. Orange means positive secant slope, blue means negative. The slope at that moment <em>is</em> the derivative.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="twinCanvas" class="visual-canvas"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>h = <span class="val" id="twinHVal">2.00</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="twinHSlider" min="0.01" max="3" step="0.01" value="2" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>x = <span class="val" id="twinXVal">1.0</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="twinXSlider" min="-3" max="3" step="0.1" value="1" />
      </div>
      <div class="visual-info" id="twinInfo"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="twin-curves"></div>
  </div>

  <!-- Velocity Ghost -->
  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">Velocity Ghost</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">A point travels along the curve, leaving ghost arrows at past positions. Each arrow points in the true tangent direction &mdash; length shows magnitude, color shows sign. Orange = rising, blue = falling.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="ghostCanvas" class="visual-canvas"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <button class="animate-btn" id="ghostBtn">&#9654; Launch</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ghostFnPow2" style="margin-left:0.5rem;">x&sup2;</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ghostFnSin">sin x</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ghostFnPow3">x&sup3;</button>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="velocity-ghost"></div>
  </div>

  <!-- Temperature Map -->
  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">Temperature Map</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">The top curve is painted by its derivative. <span style="color:#f97316">Orange</span> = rising fast, <span style="color:#94a3b8">grey</span> = flat, <span style="color:#60a5fa">blue</span> = falling. Below it, f&prime;(x) itself, with color showing whether that derivative curve is rising or falling.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="tempCanvas" class="visual-canvas"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Function</label>
        <button class="func-btn active" id="tempFnSin">sin x</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="tempFnPow2">x&sup2;</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="tempFnPow3">x&sup3;</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="tempFnExp">e^x</button>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="temperature-map"></div>
  </div>

  <!-- Music of Slope -->
  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">Music of Slope</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">The derivative becomes sound. Move the point &mdash; the pitch rises when the slope rises, falls when it falls. Flat curve = silence at middle C.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="musicCanvas" class="visual-canvas" style="height:120px;"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>x = <span class="val" id="musicXVal">0.0</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="musicXSlider" min="-4" max="4" step="0.05" value="0" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <button class="animate-btn" id="musicBtn">&#9654; Play</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="musicFnSin" style="margin-left:0.5rem;">sin x</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="musicFnPow2">x&sup2;</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="musicFnPow3">x&sup3;</button>
      </div>
      <div class="visual-info" id="musicInfo"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="music-of-slope"></div>
  </div>

</section>

<section class="frontier">
  <h2>6. Partial derivatives: the freeze-frame mountain</h2>
  <p class="frontier-intro">
    You stand on a surface <span class="math-inline" data-tex="z=f(x,y)"></span> like a mountain at night.
    You only get one flashlight beam at a time.
    Flashlight east-west gives one slope. Flashlight north-south gives another.
    With <span class="math-inline" data-tex="y"></span> frozen, your local steepness is
    <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}"></span>.
    With <span class="math-inline" data-tex="x"></span> frozen, it is
    <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}"></span>.
    Same point. Different questions. Different truths.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is the core leap from single-variable calculus to multivariable calculus:
    slope is no longer one number by default. It depends on which direction you allow motion.
  </p>

  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">Freeze-Frame Mountain</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">The purple surface is one function <span class="math-inline" data-tex="f(x,y)"></span>. Orange slice: move in x with y frozen. Blue slice: move in y with x frozen. Lock one direction and watch how the local slope changes.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="partialCanvas" class="visual-canvas" style="height:300px;"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>x = <span class="val" id="partialXVal">0.0</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="partialXSlider" min="-3" max="3" step="0.1" value="0" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>y = <span class="val" id="partialYVal">0.0</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="partialYSlider" min="-3" max="3" step="0.1" value="0" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Freeze direction</label>
        <button class="func-btn active" id="partialModeY">Lock y (read <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\partial f / \\partial x"></span>)</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="partialModeX">Lock x (read <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\partial f / \\partial y"></span>)</button>
      </div>
      <div class="slope-display frontier-slope-display">
        <div class="slope-badge"><span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\partial f/\\partial x"></span>: <span id="partialDxVal">&mdash;</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge"><span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\partial f/\\partial y"></span>: <span id="partialDyVal">&mdash;</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge"><span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\lVert\\nabla f\\rVert"></span>: <span id="partialGradVal">&mdash;</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge">steepest heading: <span id="partialDirVal">&mdash;</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="visual-info" id="partialInfo"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="freeze-frame-mountain"></div>
  </div>

  <h2>7. Integrals: the area ledger</h2>
  <p class="frontier-intro">
    Think of an integral as accounting, not coloring.
    Every thin strip is a transaction:
    <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\Delta A \\approx f(x)\\Delta x"></span>.
    Above the axis is a deposit. Below the axis is a withdrawal.
    The final statement is <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\int_a^b f(x)\\,dx"></span>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is why a dramatic graph can still net near zero: positive and negative territory can cancel almost perfectly.
  </p>

  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">The Area Ledger</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">Bars stream into a running balance. Orange bars add. Blue bars subtract. Compare left, midpoint, and right accounting rules while changing the range and number of slices.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="ledgerCanvas" class="visual-canvas" style="height:270px;"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Function</label>
        <button class="func-btn active" id="ledgerFnWave">sin x + 0.25x</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ledgerFnCubic">0.2x^3 - x</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ledgerFnBump">e^(-x^2) - 0.35</button>
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>a = <span class="val" id="ledgerAVal">-2.5</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="ledgerASlider" min="-3.5" max="2.0" step="0.1" value="-2.5" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>b = <span class="val" id="ledgerBVal">2.5</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="ledgerBSlider" min="-2.0" max="3.5" step="0.1" value="2.5" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Slices n = <span class="val" id="ledgerNVal">28</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="ledgerNSlider" min="4" max="80" step="1" value="28" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Rule</label>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ledgerMethodLeft">Left</button>
        <button class="func-btn active" id="ledgerMethodMid">Midpoint</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="ledgerMethodRight">Right</button>
      </div>
      <div class="ledger-balance">
        <div class="slope-badge">Deposits: <span id="ledgerPosVal">0.000</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge">Withdrawals: <span id="ledgerNegVal">0.000</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge">Net: <span id="ledgerNetVal">0.000</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge">Reference: <span id="ledgerExactVal">0.000</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge">Error: <span id="ledgerErrVal">0.000</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="visual-info" id="ledgerInfo"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="area-ledger"></div>
  </div>

  <h2>8. Differential equations: local rule, global fate</h2>
  <p class="frontier-intro">
    A differential equation does not hand you the whole story first.
    It gives a local law: <span class="math-inline" data-tex="\\frac{dy}{dx}=g(x,y)"></span>.
    At each point, it whispers only the next tilt. Once you choose one initial condition,
    a full trajectory unfolds.
  </p>
  <p>
    In this field, arrows are local instructions.
    One seed point turns those local instructions into a complete fate line.
  </p>
  <div class="ode-howto">
    <div class="ode-howto-title">How to read this</div>
    <div class="ode-howto-steps">
      <span>1. Arrow angle shows the local derivative <span class="math-inline" data-tex="y'"></span>.</span>
      <span>2. Tap the field to plant seed points (initial conditions).</span>
      <span>3. Each seed grows into a full trajectory: local rule, global fate.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="visual-card">
    <div class="visual-header">
      <div class="visual-title">Local Rule, Global Fate</div>
      <div class="visual-desc">Arrow field = local derivative rule. White curve = the unique solution through your chosen seed point. Tap anywhere on the field to set a new initial condition.</div>
    </div>
    <canvas id="odeCanvas" class="visual-canvas" style="height:290px;"></canvas>
    <div class="visual-controls">
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Equation</label>
        <button class="func-btn active" id="odeEqGrowth">y' = y</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="odeEqLogistic">y' = 1.2y(1 - y/2)</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="odeEqDriven">y' = sin(x) - 0.6y</button>
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Seeds: <span class="val" id="odeSeedCount">1</span></label>
        <button class="func-btn" id="odeResetBtn">Reset default seed</button>
        <button class="func-btn" id="odeClearBtn">Clear seeds</button>
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label><span id="odeParamALabel">growth rate r</span> = <span class="val" id="odeParamAVal">1.00</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="odeParamASlider" min="-2.0" max="2.0" step="0.05" value="1.0" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row" id="odeParamBRow">
        <label><span id="odeParamBLabel">carrying capacity K</span> = <span class="val" id="odeParamBVal">2.00</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="odeParamBSlider" min="0.3" max="3.5" step="0.05" value="2.0" />
      </div>
      <div class="control-row">
        <label>Active seed: x<sub>0</sub> = <span class="val" id="odeX0Val">-2.0</span>, y<sub>0</sub> = <span class="val" id="odeY0Val">0.8</span></label>
      </div>
      <div class="slope-display frontier-slope-display">
        <div class="slope-badge">slope at seed: <span id="odeSlopeVal">&mdash;</span></div>
        <div class="slope-badge">local behavior: <span id="odeTrendVal">&mdash;</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="visual-info" id="odeInfo">Tap or click inside the field to pick a new initial condition.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="viz-qa" data-viz-id="local-rule-global-fate"></div>
  </div>
</section>

